.TH vzlist 8 "12 Sep 2006" "OpenVZ" "Virtual Environments"
.SH NAME
vzlist \- VE listing utility
.SH SYNOPSIS
vzlist [\fB-a\fR] [\fB-o\fR \fIname\fR[,\fIname\fR...]]
 [\fB-s\fR [\fI-\fR]\fIname\fR] [\fB-h\fR \fIpattern\fR]
 [\fB-H\fR] [\fB-S\fR] [\fB-n\fR] [\fB-N\fR <\fI-pattern\fR>]
 [\fIveid\fR [\fIveid\fR ..] | \fB-1\fR]
.PP
vzlist \fB-L\fR
.SH DESCRIPTION
This utility is used for listing VEs. By default only running VEs are listed.
If \fIveid\fR is/are specified, only specified VEs are displayed.
VE ID of \fB-1\fR is used to output VE IDs only, one per line.
.SH OPTIONS
.IP "\fB--all\fR, \fB-a\fR"
list all VEs.
.IP "\fB--sort\fR, \fB-s\fR"
specify sorting order, the '-' before parameter means sort in reverse order
.IP "\fB--hostname\fR, \fB-h\fR  <\fIpattern\fR>"
display only VEes whose hostname matches the \fIpattern\fR.
The following wildcard characters can be used: \fB*\fR, \fB?\fR, \fB[]\fR.
Note that wildcard characters should be properly escaped
to avoid expansion by shell.
.IP "\fB--name\fR, \fB-n\fR "
display VE name.
.IP "\fB--name_filter\fR, \fB-N\fR  <\fIpattern\fR>"
display only VEs whose hostname matches the \fIpattern\fR.
.IP "\fB--no-header\fR, \fB-H\fR"
suppress displaying header
.IP "\fB--stopped -S\fR"
display only stopped VEs
.IP "\fB--list -L\fR"
list all format specifiers

